The problem requires finding the largest number of substrings that can be formed from a given string, where each substring is a single character. We can solve this problem by iterating through the string once and counting the occurrences of each character. If a character has a count of 0, we increment k, which represents the number of substrings. Finally, we return the maximum value of k.

The time complexity is O(n) because we iterate through the string once. The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a constant amount of space for the count array. The energy implications are low because the algorithm only performs a single pass through the string and does not require any additional resources.

